class Solution {
    public long maximumSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {
        long ans = Long.MIN_VALUE;
        long sum = 0;
        Map<Integer, Long> minS = new HashMap<>();
        for (int x : nums) {
            long s1 = sum - x;
            long s2 = minS.getOrDefault(x + k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            ans = Math.max(ans, sum + x - Math.min(s1, s2));
            minS.merge(x, sum, Math::min);
            sum += x;
        }
        return ans > Long.MIN_VALUE / 4 ? ans : 0;
    }
}
```

In this code, the variable ans keeps track of the maximum sum of a good subarray seen so far, while sum keeps track of the sum of the current subarray. The HashMap minS stores the minimum sum of subarrays ending at each index. For each element x in the array nums, we calculate the minimum sum of a subarray ending at the current index, which is the sum of the subarray ending at the previous index minus x. We also look up the minimum sum of a subarray ending at the index corresponding to x + k in the HashMap. We update ans if necessary and then update the minimum sum of subarrays ending at the current index in the HashMap. Finally, we update sum by adding x. If ans is greater than Long.MIN_VALUE / 4, it means we have found at least one good subarray, so we return ans. Otherwise, we return 0.

